{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"079b1f71-3cbb-4196-b023-399715519f1c","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in the container, use `dotnet-trace` as a [global tool from a sidecar](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace) or copy the binary in.\n- For production-safe, lower-overhead collection, use **`--profile cpu-sampling`** (default 10ms interval) rather than verbose event tracing.\n- Copy the file out with `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"92ebe24b-e3a0-4d25-9157-3e12013eda01","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":353,"requestId":"2173:2B0E8:3B7561:4578E9:69F00D12"},"id":"006706e5-05a9-4e40-ac6c-15a2aa3b866d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:27:56.543Z","parentId":"6ed7eaa2-dcb8-43f1-b0ba-d61ded5fccf6"}
